title: Elastic Scattering of 40-MeV Protons from Isotopes Of Fe, Ni and Cu.

x4freetext: Elastic Scattering of 40-MeV Protons from Isotopes

x4codes.hlp: University of Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN, United States of America

x4freetext: Five Nuclide were Used in these Measurements-
Fe-54, Fe-56, Ni-58, Ni-60 and Cu-65.
Their Isotopic Composition was Determined by the Oak
Ridge Laboratory at Their Time of Fabrication.
Except For the Iron Target, which was 95% Fe-54, the
Targets were Monoisotopic to Greater Than 98%. They
The Telescope Arrangement was Used to Shield the Na-I
Crystal from Charged Particles Emanating Elsewhere Than

x4codes.hlp: University of Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN, United States of America

x4freetext: The Errors For the Present Measurements were Found to
Be Strongly Dependent Upon the Scattering Angle at
Which the Measurement was Taken and Upon the Particular
The Probable Error For the Experimental Unaveraged
Absolute Cross Section Lies from +-6% to +-10% For
Fe-54, Fe-56, Ni-58 and from +-7% to +-11% For Ni-60
Background was Negligible at Angles Above 20 Degrees.
Below 20 Degrees, Backgrond Corrections were Applied to
The Data to Account For Protons Scattered from the Beam
Collimating Slits or from the Mylar Exit Window of the
Another Correction Which was Applied to All the Data
Concerned the Effects of Nuclear Interactions Made by
Protons Entering in the Detector Crystal. Such
Interactions would Tend to Decrease the Measured
Elastic Scattering Cross Sections. Johnston and Swenson
Have Investigated this Effect Carefully and have Come
To the Conclusion That, For 40-MeV Protons, a 1.9%
Correction Should be Applied to the Data to Account For
It. This Correction has Been Applied.

x4freetext: - By Authors - All Formulas Used in the Calculations
Are Nonrelativistic. The Error Involved Due to Use of
Nonrelativistic Formulas Amounts to Less Than 0.3%.
